{"author":"RebarBotNava","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Context\n\nrebar has no general mechanism to apply an idempotent setup/config change to an\nALREADY-EXISTING install. Init-time `_migrate_*`/`_ensure_*` functions (e.g.\n`_migrate_gc_config`) run only at `init`/re-init, so a fix shipped after a store was\ninitialized never reaches it unless someone re-inits — exactly the gap the `gc.auto=0`\nlegacy-store issue exposed (fixed operationally; the mechanism is what's missing).\nDiscovered from the gc discussion (e3d0).\n\n**School B (desired-state / convergent), not School A (ordered ledger).** This class\nof change (stateless config invariants) is textbook desired-state: idempotent,\nsafe-to-re-run, drift-correcting. Prior art converged on this shape — Ansible/Puppet/\nChef resources are check-then-act (no-op when already converged; `changed` vs `ok`),\nKubernetes controllers reconcile level-triggered every loop, systemd-tmpfiles ensures\nstate. We deliberately do NOT build an ordered version ledger (Alembic/Flyway/Rails)\n— those exist for irreversible, unsafe-to-rerun migrations, which ours are not. The\nA-tier ledger (committed store-format version, ordered, fail-closed on too-new) is\ncaptured future work (see docs/migrations.md + the sibling `rebar doctor` idea dabb).\n\n## Design (agreed via brainstorm)\n\n**Ensure-registry (`ensures.py`).** A dedicated module holding a registry of ensure\nunits, each with a stable id and a **check-then-act** callable that no-ops when already\nconverged and reports `changed`/`ok` (Ansible model). `run_ensures()` runs ALL units\n**unconditionally** (never gated on a marker — K8s drift-correction discipline),\nreturns per-unit changed/ok + any failures, and records the set of cleanly-applied ids.\nMigrate all 5 current init-time idempotent steps in: gc-config, merge=ours driver,\ngitattributes (check-then-commit — the only step with an observable commit side effect),\nscratch-exclude, env-id seed.\n\n**Entry points (non-hot) that run the sweep:** init/re-init (always), `rebar fsck --fix`\n(opt-in — see below), MCP server startup (after the --help check). The sweep never runs\non the hot write path and never on pure reads.\n\n**Applied-set marker + write-path pending-hint (Rails `CheckPending`, hardened).**\n- `.ensure-applied` — a git-ignored, per-environment, atomically-written file holding the\n  SET of cleanly-applied ensure ids (multi-actor store → a set, not a single int; no\n  legacy int is ever shipped, so absent/garbage → empty set → next sweep converges).\n- Write-path hook at the universal chokepoint `event_append.write_and_push` (lazy import\n  to avoid coupling the hot path's import graph): compute `pending = available_ids −\n  applied_ids` **once per process** and cache the boolean (the verdict can't change\n  mid-process; keyed on binary version + registry signature — Rails 6.1's cached-boolean\n  fix, avoiding its 8–10ms/request v1 mistake). A converged store therefore adds ≤1 file\n  read per process and does nothing thereafter.\n- Emit a `WARNING` (rebar logger) pointing to `rebar fsck --fix` ONLY when pending AND\n  `last_hinted_at` (`.ensure-hinted`, atomic) is older than 24h (update-notifier /\n  HOMEBREW_AUTO_UPDATE_SECS standard — persisted timestamp, never per-process).\n  Suppressible via env var. The hint path swallows exceptions tightly (marker read +\n  timestamp write only) and logs at debug — a write must NEVER fail on the nag machinery.\n- The marker gates the HINT ONLY, never the repair. A fresh auto-init'd worktree is\n  converged from init → never hints; the hint fires only after a binary upgrade without\n  re-init/fsck.\n\n**fsck: read-only default, `--fix` heals.** Plain `rebar fsck` REPORTS an\n`ensures: N/M applied` line and mutates nothing new (honors `no_mutate`; preserves the\ngit-fsck-is-read-only convention). `rebar fsck --fix` runs `run_ensures()`. This defuses\nthe read-shaped-verb-mutates footgun now; the sibling `rebar doctor` epic (dabb, blocked\non this) later subsumes the healing surface.\n\n**Accepted trade-offs:** a long-lived MCP server converges at boot but does not re-sweep\nmid-life (drift caught at next `fsck --fix`); a permanently-failing ensure keeps its id\nout of the set and is named in the rate-limited hint (no auto-backoff in v1).\n\n## Workstreams (child stories)\n- WS1 ensure-registry (`ensures.py`) + migrate the 5 check-then-act steps + init wiring + applied-set write\n- WS2 applied-set marker + write-path pending-hint (cached once/proc + 24h timestamp rate-limit + suppress + fail-silent)\n- WS3 `fsck --fix` (read-only default, reports `ensures: N/M`) + MCP server-startup wiring (byte-parity updated)\n- WS4 `docs/migrations.md` (how to add an ensure; entry points; marker; hint; hot-path contract; A-tier future)\n- WS5 tests: git-level idempotency, hot-path regression, staleness-hint (rate-limit/suppress/fresh-worktree-silent), concurrency, no_mutate, absent-marker\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] An idempotent `ensure_*` registry (`ensures.py`) generalizes the 5 init-time steps; each unit is check-then-act (second run = zero changes, zero commits)\n- [ ] `run_ensures()` runs unconditionally at init/re-init, `fsck --fix`, and MCP server startup; it is NEVER gated on the marker (drift is always corrected)\n- [ ] Plain `rebar fsck` is read-only, reports `ensures: N/M applied`, and mutates nothing new; `rebar fsck --fix` heals and is git-level idempotent (twice → zero new commits)\n- [ ] A write-path-only pending-hint points users to `rebar fsck --fix`; pure reads are untouched; a converged store adds ≤1 file read per process on writes; the hint never fails a write\n- [ ] The hint is rate-limited to ≤1 per 24h per environment (persisted timestamp), is suppressible via env var, and a fresh auto-init'd worktree never hints\n- [ ] Applied-set marker is atomic + concurrency-safe under parallel agents; absent/garbage marker degrades to empty-set (no crash, no re-commit storm)\n- [ ] Hot-path regression test: ticket-mutation ops may hint but never invoke `run_ensures` (no git-config subprocess; ≤1 marker read/process)\n- [ ] `docs/migrations.md` documents the pattern reuse and the marker-gates-hint-never-repair invariant; A-tier (committed store-format version + ordered ledger, fail-closed on too-new) captured as future work\n- [ ] gc-config normalization is the documented reference ensure unit"}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783568977371919001,"uuid":"47347e15-1485-433e-b7a1-127f10f71f4a"}